eMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Nevill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Neville","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud de Nevill was born about 1361, in Brampton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Philip Neville ,Lord of Scotton, was 21 and her mother, Sarah, was 18. She married Sir JOHN De BUSSEY in 1382. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1398, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 38."},"et":{"Abt 1361–1398":"umbes 1361–1398","1361–1398":"1361–1398","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1380–1459":"1380–1459","–1428":"–1428","1342–1374":"1342–1374","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","24 August 1374":"24. august 1374","1459":"1459","Abt 1361":"umbes 1361","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1344":"1344","1399":"1399","1398":"1398","1342":"1342","1428":"1428","Of, Brampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Brampton, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dembleby, Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Dembleby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1361–1398":"noin 1361–1398","1361–1398":"1361–1398","1350–1399":"1350–1399","1380–1459":"1380–1459